The paper deals with the problem of event series completion in a knowledge graph, which involves predicting sub-event relations and inferring real-world events that are missing in the knowledge graph. This task involves techniques from artificial intelligence (cs.AI) such as supervised learning, as well as database (cs.DB) and information retrieval (cs.IR) techniques for working with knowledge graphs. The paper also mentions the use of natural language processing (cs.CL) techniques for extracting information from text. Finally, the paper evaluates its approach using precision metrics, which is a common evaluation metric in machine learning (cs.LG).
